summary.seg: This manuscript contains the Acts of the Council of Ephesus (431 CE). The council was summoned by emperor Theodosios II and was focused on the conflict between the Christology of the Antiochian school, represented by Nestorius, bishop of Constantinople, and of the Alexandrian school, represented by Cyril, bishop of Alexandria.
The codex was copied in the first half of the 16th century in Italy by Bartolomeo Zanetti, prolific scribe and printer, active in Venice, Florence and Rome.

support.material: ff. [i]-[iv], [v] Western paper. Watermarks: Gothic letter P surmounted by a four-leaf clover ( 63 20 ) , comparable (although with differences) to Piccard online Buchstabe P no. DE4500-PO-110862 , which is dated to 1537.

ff. 1-314 Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. 1-80, 123/126, 226-227 Anchor in a circle surmounted by a five-point star, countermark A9
( 68 43 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Sosower Ancre 88 , which is dated to 1554 (Venice), and to Briquet Ancre 507 , which is dated to 1529.
ff. 81-122, 124, 127-225, 228-264, 269-270 Anchor in a circle surmounted by a five-point star, countermark BE
( 63 43 ) in the centre of the leaf, identical to Sosower Ancre 49 , which is dated to ca. 1553.
ff. 265-268, 271-314 Anchor in a circle surmounted by a five-point star, countermark TC with clover ( 65 40 ) in the centre of the leaf, identical to Sosower Ancre 96 , which is dated to ca. 1550-1552.

foliation.p: Modern pencil foliation, in Arabic numerals, in the upper right-hand margin, from 1 to 314; four leaves at the beginning and one at the end of the manuscript are unnumbered: [i]-[iv] + 1-314 + [v].
Another modern pencil foliation, in Arabic numerals, in the upper right-hand margin, from 1 ( f. [i] recto) to 5 f. 1r) has been erased.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of quaternions and 3 senions.
collation.signatures: Greek signatures in the lower margin, right, near the edge, from α΄ (1, f. 1r) to μ΄ (40, f. 314r), written by the scribe in red or brown ink.
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords by the scribe, written from the top down, in the lower margin of the last leaf of each quire, near the gutter.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition. The lower right-hand edge of f. 104r has been cut. Along the edges of the leaves there are passim traces of red ink, from the coloured edges (see e.g. f. [i] recto).

handNote.p: ff.1r-314r Hand A: the texts have been written by Bartolomeo Zanetti (1486/1487-1547 at least) Zanetti, Bartholomeo, 1486 or 1487- (Bartholomaeus Zanettus, RGK I, 31; on the scribe see also RGK II 43; RGK III, 56)
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.
The scribe wrote a few marginal annotations.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. 1r there is a simple undulated linear frieze with clover-leaves at both ends.
Initials in ekthesis in red ink are decorated with a simple vegetal motif, see e.g. f. 17v.

additions.p: On the left pastedown are written the present shelfmark, B.4.10, and two other, which have been erased, C.4.24 and B.IV.9.

On f. [i] recto there is an indication about the contents in the upper part of the leaf, Epistolae Cyrilli ad Nestorium itemque Nestorii ad Cyrillum vid. pag, seq. 5 . Below, there is a signature, C.4.24
Passim there are modern pencil annotations containing indications about a few blank lines left by the scribe: f. 197r Suppl. ex libro impresso p. 181 (a similar case occurs on f. 204r).

binding.p: Western early modern binding, full parchment cover over pasteboards. Blind tooling on both covers: a rectangular frame filled with a vegetal motif of palmettes. On the left cover there is a vegetal ornament in the centre of the frame. The edges are painted in red. On the spine are glued three paper labels with the shelfmark. 370 250 75
binding.condition: The cover is damaged and worn out around the edges, and there are scraps and some stains.

origin.p: The manuscript was copied in the first half of the 16th century by the scribe and printer Bartolomeo Zanetti, in Italy.

history.acquisition: In all likelihood, the manuscript was donated to Trinity College Library by Thomas Nevile (ca. 1548-1615) Nevile, Thomas, -1615 , Master of Trinity College and Dean of Canterbury, in the years 1611-1612 (for the provenance from Nevile, see James (1900), pp. xxii and 147; for the date of the donation see P. Gaskell, Trinity College Library: the first 150 years. The Sandars Lectures 1978-9 (Cambridge, 1980), p. 81). On the left pastedown is pasted the Trinity College bookplate. Stamps of Trinity College Library are present on ff. 1r, 6r, 314r.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) partly draws on M. R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, p. 147.
